cotland, United Kingdom","Kintyre, Argyll, Scotland":"Kintyre, Argyll, Scotland","Craig, Angus, Scotland":"Craig, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ayr, South Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Muir","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived on a moor, from Older Scots <i>muir</i> ‘moor’ (an expanse of bare, wild upland country). There has been some confusion with   Mure  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mure","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): variant of   Morea  .","Scottish: variant of   Muir  .","English: occupational name from Old French <i>muer</i> ‘mewer’, i.e. someone who tended to hawks in the cages in which they were kept while moulting. Compare   Mew  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir David Muir of Polkelly was born in 1174, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Reginald Muir of Polkelly, King of the Northern Isles and Argyll \"having descended from the O'Moores of Ireland. The Muirs of Polkelly may have been the senior Muir line.\", was 25 and his mother, Fonia Moray, was 29. He married Lady Isabel Graham about 1200, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1249, in his hometown, at the age of 75, and was buried in Ayrshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1174–1249":"1174–1249","1176–1296":"1176–1296","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1233–1285":"1233–1285","1234–1295":"1234–1295","1149–1199":"1149–1199","1145–1200":"1145–1200","1176":"1176","1285":"1285","1296":"1296","1174":"1174","1295":"1295","1280":"1280","1249":"1249","1149":"1149","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1233":"1233","1145":"1145","1199":"1199","about 1200":"umbes 1200","about 1234":"umbes 1234","Polkelly, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kintyre, Argyll, Scotland":"Kintyre, Argyll, Scotland","Craig, Angus, Scotland":"Craig, Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Ayr, South Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1174–1249":"1174–1249","1176–1296":"1176–1296","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1233–1285":"1233–1285","1234–1295":"1234–1295","1149–1199":"1149–1199","1145–1200":"1145–1200","1176":"1176","1285":"1285","1296":"1296","1174":"1174","1295":"1295","1280":"1280","1249":"1249","1149":"1149","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1233":"1233",